comments.text: This is a good point. Would be interesting to track where the readmissions come from (facility or home). You probably already have a good idea but maybe we can work to get that data.

Agree this is a very good point.Although it seems daunting, I wonder how we work with nursing homes to prepare and serve meals low in sodium for our heart failure patients. The government has gotten involved in schools perhaps it is time that they also step in for nursing home patients to ensure they get the diet restrictions and/or requirements that are needed.

I wonder how many readmissions are related to uncontrolled diet due to Nursing Homes' limited dietary options. This has come up many times, and I have mentioned it to the CNS, Nurse Manager, NPs and Consultants. Patients eat sodium laden meals prepared at nursing homes which could result in many readmissions. This also applies for Assisted Living Facilities.  
 
I had a patient's son tell me just today that his dad stayed out of the hospital for 2 years with a sodium controlled diet. Now he is in the Nursing Home and his diet is not controlled at all and this has resulted in readmissions. The son expressed his frustration especially when he saw all of the prepackaged foods in the NH kitchen, but also said, that he needed the overall cares of the facility at this time.

Totally agree! You would think medicare would want to be more involved in this due to the unnecessary expense of patients in and out with heart failure exacerbation. I think that's a good idea to track particular nursing facilities and see if we can shed light on some that we see are correlated with hospital readmissions, particularly heart failure. Then maybe we could bring this up to medicare (somehow) and this could facilitate some nutrition policy changes.

When talking with patients, I note that many of them have little culinary skills. Many do not know how to read a food label and Na tends to hide in everything even minimally processed.  Note that the local Hyvee has dietician on site for consult. 
For our sake, it may worthwhile tracking nursing homes with good or bad records concerning diet compliance.

I agree with the nursing home diet...my MIL was admitted to an assisted living/rehab unit and their kitchen had to go way out of their way to give her a low sodium diet.  Hard to believe out of all those people at the facility, that she was the only one who needed low sodium.  Nursing homes get knocked down a few points if residences lose weight while In their facilities....so maybe they just give them whatever tastes good, not what is best for their condition.
Sherry-I wasnt aware that NH got penalized when pts lose weight.
How about outreach resources such as Meals on Wheels? Are there limited dietary options there as well?

Kim Poe & Bethany- great points! So how would we go about alerting: the government aka Medicare aka the entity who imposes the fines on the hospitals for heart failure readmissions? There seems to be some critical information here that could 1) help the pateints manage heart failure exacerbations and  2) Make Nursing Homes & Assisted Living Facilities accountable just as hospitals are.

Recently I had a patient here with heart failure who was recieving meals on wheels. I was surprised to learn that they are not able to accomodate these restrictions. My patient needed both a low sodium and diabetic diet, and she was not able to get this thru her meals on wheels.
I wonder if this could be some kind of community/cardiology team project to focus on our local nursing homes???
I think that is a lovely idea-perhaps a pilot via Employee Community Health?  Would the cost be offset by the diminshed cost of readmission?

I spoke with a patient (that happens to be a nurse in another hospital in the cardiology field) and she said the way they try to prevent hospital readmissions is by phone call follow ups. How do patients qualify for the heart failure clinic or Care Transitions programs? Many of our patients would benifit from home health care for education/assessments but do not qualify.

I would agree with both-the value of providing personalized or genomic education, as well as the real value of bringing in the perspective and experiences of the nurses who represent the front line of our outpatient process.  Both apt observations.

As we consider ways to improve our heart failure education class, I believe it would be important to consider the staff (nurses/NPs/PAs) that deal with clinical follow-ups. 
- What do they find are the common obstacles for patients once they are outside of the hospital and making an effort to stay out?
- Are they asking questions that we may not have covered in our education?
This may be helpful feedback to enhance the education we provide on the floor.
I invite anyone in the pilot that has heard from clinic staff to post any new ideas on their behalf.

It would be interesting to get their (the outpatient heart failure RN/NP/PA) input. Nevertheless, I think heart failure education should be tailored to each patient and their lifestyle (ie. identifying potential setbacks in their native environment). Maybe the education would be better retained if patients could independently APPLY those principles during hospitalization to increase their chance of success after discharge. Yes, the hospital environment is perfectly structured for this, but what if we also made patients accountable for tracking their fluid intake & daily weight, which would help establish a necessary habit even before they returned home?

We do have pink sheets for tracking fluid intake, but they are not frequently utilized. Sodium in the hospital is a challege because of the menu. The old  menu has sodium listed in meq or the new general menu that just has the salt shaker pictured next to high sodium items. This doesn't allow patients to track there sodium in mg.

I wonder if it would be helpful to delineate plans of care and expectations very plainly and in detail at discharge. It seems that a number of patients come back early because they don't understand their disease neither our discharge instructions.

I think it is helpful to have "teach-back cheat sheets" about patient's disease processes. Until I am super confident in my own knowledge I appreciate knowing I am asking the right questions! I know I have used something like this with coumadin teaching.

I notice the HF readmit rate peaking in August.  Does this happen every year?  Does it have anything to do with the heat?  Do outpatient providers have any strategies to teach patients strategies to deal with a heat wave?

INteresting thought. For one thing, the connection to heat might be d/t consuming fluids there by adding to non-compliance(potentially). As for the data tailored to re-admission - I am not sure as the 30 day re-admission is tied to ACA and tends to e more recent.
I wonder what the readmission rates are in climates that are always warmer, like texas for example.
Jill, possibly, however, the body, never the less, would still require more fluids during increased temperatures to remain healthy.

comment_threads.title: Nursing Home Patients and Sodium Control

charts.definition:
# What is this?
Hospital, CV Specialty & Physician Level: Patient readmission for any cause within 30 days from the date of discharge.  This is specifically for patients discharged from the hospital with a principal discharge diagnosis of heart failure (HF).  

# Where does this data come from?
Hospital, CV Specialty, & Physician Level: UHC (University Health Consortium) [www.uhc.edu](http://www.uhc.edu/)

# Where does this target come from?
Target is set by CMS (Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services) and represents the National Upper Quartile cut-off point. Target is adjusted to UHC Data.

# What is the financial impact for 4 Domitilla?
St. Marys Hospital will experience an additional estimated reimbursement penalty of ~$250.000 from the Federal Readmission Reduction Program. (The penalization amount is decided based on where your hospital ranks against the nation. This penalty could increase significantly more if the national average improves).

# How often is the data updated?
Monthly. We upload the UHC (or DSS) data on the 22nd of each month (currently a 1 month delay).  You’re looking at a years’ worth of data.

# Who can I ask? 
* Dr. Margaret Redfield, Director of Circulatory Failure; Consultant - Cardiology Non-Invasive [redfield.margaret@mayo.edu](mailto:redfield.margaret@mayo.edu)
* Dr. Grace Lin, Director of Heart Failure Clinic; Consultant - Cardiology Non-Invasive [lin.grace@mayo.edu](mailto:lin.grace@mayo.edu)
